He is like the man of whom Homer
wrote in <i>Denunciation </i>, "Clanless

01:08:08.800 --> 01:08:11.640
and lawless and hearthless is he."

01:08:11.640 --> 01:08:15.150
So it's important that
Aristotle fixes on this idea

01:08:15.150 --> 01:08:20.400
of being separated from the
city based on his own nature

01:08:20.400 --> 01:08:22.010
and not of some accident.

01:08:22.010 --> 01:08:25.410
So here we have Shylock being
separated in the ghetto based

01:08:25.410 --> 01:08:30.370
on his nature of being a Jew.

01:08:30.370 --> 01:08:34.410
Alasdair MacIntyre,
interpreting Aristotle passage,

01:08:34.410 --> 01:08:37.780
writes that "A human being,
separated from the polis,"

01:08:37.780 --> 01:08:40.820
from the city, "is
thereby deprived of some

01:08:40.820 --> 01:08:44.810
of the essential attributes
of a human being."

01:08:44.810 --> 01:08:47.950
MacIntyre aligns Aristotle
with Homer and Sophocles

01:08:47.950 --> 01:08:51.700
as early thinkers who believe
that, quote, "A human being

01:08:51.700 --> 01:08:55.420
who is separated from his
social group is also deprived

01:08:55.420 --> 01:08:59.190
of the capacity for justice."

01:08:59.190 --> 01:09:02.430
He says that, according
to Aristotle, quote,

01:09:02.430 --> 01:09:04.030
"Separated from the polis,

01:09:04.030 --> 01:09:08.750
what could have been a human being
becomes instead a wild animal."

01:09:08.750 --> 01:09:12.260
So there's this idea
that the nature --

01:09:12.260 --> 01:09:20.070
that separation in and of
itself creates a lack of justice

01:09:20.070 --> 01:09:22.450
in the separated population.

01:09:22.450 --> 01:09:26.830 position:56%
And, according to Aristotle, this
idea that there's a fallback to kind

01:09:26.830 --> 01:09:30.340 position:56%
of wild instinctual feelings instead

01:09:30.340 --> 01:09:34.280
of being governed by
legal principles.

01:09:34.280 --> 01:09:39.140 position:56%
Shylock, being a political animal,
gets set off, exhibits the handicaps

01:09:39.140 --> 01:09:42.890
of separation from other
members of the city of Venice.

01:09:42.890 --> 01:09:47.920 position:56%
He can be hardly expected to respond
justly in contract or in court

01:09:47.920 --> 01:09:49.940
when he is not a full
member of the polis.

01:09:49.940 --> 01:09:55.010
The explicit and implicit
violence of the penalty he includes

01:09:55.010 --> 01:09:59.750
in the bond is understandable
given that he has been deprived

01:09:59.750 --> 01:10:05.050
of the capacity for justice and
may be closer to a wild animal.

01:10:05.050 --> 01:10:08.850
For an extreme example
of this outcome

01:10:08.850 --> 01:10:12.580
of exclusion you can
take a look at Barabas

01:10:12.580 --> 01:10:14.770
in Marlowe's <i>Jew of Malta </i>, right?

01:10:14.770 --> 01:10:17.460
So a lot of -- it's
possible that Shakespeare --

01:10:17.460 --> 01:10:18.760
there were a lot of --

01:10:18.760 --> 01:10:22.300
several things involving Jews
that were happening in England

01:10:22.300 --> 01:10:25.070
about the time Shakespeare
wrote <i>The Merchant of Venice </i>.

01:10:25.070 --> 01:10:28.970
But one of them was that
Marlowe had had a great deal

01:10:28.970 --> 01:10:31.820
of success writing
<i>The Jew of Malta </i>.

01:10:31.820 --> 01:10:35.880
And Barabas is a very different
character than Shylock.

01:10:35.880 --> 01:10:40.330
If the court in Venice were
forced to recognize the legal

01:10:40.330 --> 01:10:43.580
and physical separations
suffered by Shylock

01:10:43.580 --> 01:10:47.960
and its effects it might
begin a process of enquiry

01:10:47.960 --> 01:10:52.690
into the justification for its
laws when applied the contracts

01:10:52.690 --> 01:10:55.010
between Jews and Christians.

01:10:55.010 --> 01:10:59.430
In any case, this might be an
approach to a kind of nascent idea

01:10:59.430 --> 01:11:02.380
of a human right to a
quality of treatment.

01:11:02.380 --> 01:11:06.540
So I'm putting together
Shakespeare's own speech,

01:11:06.540 --> 01:11:09.950
which I just read to
you, and Aristotle.

01:11:09.950 --> 01:11:11.250
All right.

01:11:11.250 --> 01:11:15.460
On a slightly different topic,
Aristotle himself opens the door

01:11:15.460 --> 01:11:17.990
to the judge acting justly.

01:11:17.990 --> 01:11:22.000
What is the responsibility of the
Duke of Venice to answer justly,

01:11:22.000 --> 01:11:27.690
to act justly, and not, perhaps,
just according to the laws.

01:11:27.690 --> 01:11:30.980
Another very influential
Aristotelian text

01:11:30.980 --> 01:11:34.570
in the Renaissance was
the <i>Nicomachean Ethics </i>.

01:11:34.570 --> 01:11:38.000
In it, Aristotle writes that
quote, "When people dispute

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:41.490
with one another they find
refuge before a judge.

01:11:41.490 --> 01:11:49.440
To go to a judge is to go to the
just, for a judge wishes to be,

01:11:49.440 --> 01:11:54.310
as it were, the just
ensouled," close quote.

01:11:54.310 --> 01:11:57.730
An effective counterargument
to using Aristotle to argue

01:11:57.730 --> 01:12:01.430
for equality of treatment
might be that Aristotle --

01:12:01.430 --> 01:12:03.930
so, also accept, accepted slavery.

01:12:03.930 --> 01:12:07.210
As you know, there was slavery
in the Greek city-states.

01:12:07.210 --> 01:12:09.550 position:56%
And it's interesting that at this --

01:12:09.550 --> 01:12:14.350
that Shylock also points out
the hypocrisy to the Christians

01:12:14.350 --> 01:12:16.240
in <i>The Merchant of
Venice </i>of the fact

01:12:16.240 --> 01:12:21.290
that they have slaves,
that they own property.

01:12:21.290 --> 01:12:24.830
And so, therefore, he's
saying, "Why cannot I not

01:12:24.830 --> 01:12:30.760
at the same time enforce my
contract for the pound of flesh?"

01:12:30.760 --> 01:12:33.940
Okay. Michelle de Montagne,
the great French Philosopher

01:12:33.940 --> 01:12:37.770
of the 16th century can also be
brought to bear to demonstrate

01:12:37.770 --> 01:12:40.900
that there was a whiff of
tolerance in the air at the time

01:12:40.900 --> 01:12:43.820
that Shakespeare wrote
<i>The Merchant of Venice </i>.

01:12:43.820 --> 01:12:47.700
Montagne was available to the
educated and Shakespeare had access

01:12:47.700 --> 01:12:52.440
to Montagne's essays as of 1580
when they were first published.

01:12:52.440 --> 01:12:56.620
He could have read them in whatever
French he had available to him.

01:12:56.620 --> 01:13:00.000
Of course, the essays became
fully available to Shakespeare

01:13:00.000 --> 01:13:03.990
when they were published in
English translation in 1603.

01:13:03.990 --> 01:13:07.410
But that was after the composition
of <i>The Merchant of Venice </i>.

01:13:07.410 --> 01:13:09.680
The relations between <i>The
Merchant of Venice </i>itself

01:13:09.680 --> 01:13:12.380
and Montagne are beside
the point here.

01:13:12.380 --> 01:13:15.020
The point is whether at the
time it would have been possible

01:13:15.020 --> 01:13:19.440
in Christian Venice to see
a way toward more tolerance

01:13:19.440 --> 01:13:21.730
with respect to laws.

01:13:21.730 --> 01:13:25.340
In fact, Montagne was at the very
beginning of the arc of toleration

01:13:25.340 --> 01:13:28.170 position:56%
that would eventually culminate
with the "Bill of Rights" in America

01:13:28.170 --> 01:13:31.930
and the "Declaration of the
Rights of Man" in France.

01:13:31.930 --> 01:13:36.670
His famous essay, <i>Of the
Cannibals </i>specifically purposes

01:13:36.670 --> 01:13:40.130
to impress Europeans with
conflicting, but legitimate,

01:13:40.130 --> 01:13:45.050
claims to knowledge in practice
exhibited by non-European peoples.

01:13:45.050 --> 01:13:47.720
In the case of the
"Essay", it was Brazilians.

01:13:47.720 --> 01:13:51.600
In John Florio's translation,
Montagne writes,

01:13:51.600 --> 01:13:53.210
"Now to return to my purpose.

01:13:53.210 --> 01:13:57.700
I find as far as I've been informed
there is nothing in that nation,

01:13:57.700 --> 01:14:02.740
Brazil, that is either barbarous
or savage unless men call

01:14:02.740 --> 01:14:08.360
that barbarism which is simply
not common to them, as, indeed,

01:14:08.360 --> 01:14:13.160
we have no other aim of truth and
reason than the example and idea

01:14:13.160 --> 01:14:17.070
of the opinions and customs
of the country we live in,

01:14:17.070 --> 01:14:22.270
where is ever perfect religion,
perfect policy, perfect

01:14:22.270 --> 01:14:24.380
and complete use of all things."

01:14:24.380 --> 01:14:28.390
So Montagne's saying that we
have to look at other groups

01:14:28.390 --> 01:14:30.350
through an understanding that,

01:14:30.350 --> 01:14:33.430
just because they do something
differently from the way we do it,

01:14:33.430 --> 01:14:36.400
doesn't mean that we have the
right to judge them or think

01:14:36.400 --> 01:14:40.430
that what they're doing is in
some way inferior to what we do.

01:14:40.430 --> 01:14:45.600 position:56%
Could the judges in the case of
Shylock's arguments not exhibit some

01:14:45.600 --> 01:14:50.170
of the toleration and humanism
Montagne evidences toward peoples

01:14:50.170 --> 01:14:51.840
far from Europe?

01:14:51.840 --> 01:14:54.270
Could toleration become
especially relevant

01:14:54.270 --> 01:14:59.510
when Shylock's ultimate punishment,
forced conversion, is considered?

01:14:59.510 --> 01:15:03.690
Okay. So, those are
[inaudible] broad human rights

01:15:03.690 --> 01:15:05.400
and toleration ideas.

01:15:05.400 --> 01:15:08.060 position:56%
To go to the ghetto more explicitly.

01:15:08.060 --> 01:15:10.620
Shakespeare never mentions
the Jewish Ghetto

01:15:10.620 --> 01:15:11.920
in <i>The Merchant of Venice </i>.

01:15:11.920 --> 01:15:15.650
This is one of the things that has
puzzled people who thought a lot

01:15:15.650 --> 01:15:17.650
about <i>The Merchant of Venice </i>.

01:15:17.650 --> 01:15:21.250
If it -- if Shakespeare
knew Venice so well,

01:15:21.250 --> 01:15:23.760 position:56%
