the Jews to leave other parts

01:20:28.980 --> 01:20:31.030
of Venice and move into the ghetto.

01:20:31.030 --> 01:20:34.790
It declared that the Jews
had to be removed [speaking

01:20:34.790 --> 01:20:39.100
in foreign language] which
means they had to be removed

01:20:39.100 --> 01:20:42.230
from the body of the city.

01:20:43.250 --> 01:20:45.680
So Shakespeare had a ready metaphor

01:20:45.680 --> 01:20:49.580
in the legal document itself
that created the ghetto.

01:20:49.580 --> 01:20:52.910
Second, the contemporary of
Shakespeare who travelled in Italy,

01:20:52.910 --> 01:20:57.190
including Venice, and published
a kind of travelogue in 1611

01:20:57.190 --> 01:21:00.630
about those adventures and
many others, spoke of the Jews

01:21:00.630 --> 01:21:05.200
who could quote, "flay many
a poor Christian's estate

01:21:05.200 --> 01:21:08.170
by their griping extortion,"
close quote.

01:21:08.170 --> 01:21:12.870
Of course Shakes wrote <i>The Merchant
of Venice </i>earlier than 1611,

01:21:12.870 --> 01:21:16.420
but this line opens the possibility
that people at the time thought

01:21:16.420 --> 01:21:19.540
of the extraction of
wealth from another person

01:21:19.540 --> 01:21:22.600
as a kind of skinning or flaying.

01:21:22.600 --> 01:21:25.680
The relation to the pound
of flesh is obvious.

01:21:25.680 --> 01:21:29.130
Related expressions today
might include skinflint

01:21:29.130 --> 01:21:33.340
or the skin off my back.

01:21:33.340 --> 01:21:44.560
Okay. And just a couple of more
quick comments about defenses

01:21:44.560 --> 01:21:46.210
that could be made for Shylock.

01:21:46.210 --> 01:21:51.270
There's the idea of "the other."

01:21:51.270 --> 01:21:55.340 position:56%
Of course this is an idea which is
