01:23:12.210 --> 01:23:14.820
in particular, with
respect to revenge.

01:23:14.820 --> 01:23:18.020
Revenge is often overlooked
and underplayed in discussions

01:23:18.020 --> 01:23:21.770
of the speech when a commentator's
emphasizing Shakespeare's empathy

01:23:21.770 --> 01:23:23.900
and compassion for Jews.

01:23:23.900 --> 01:23:28.990
As Shylock says, "If you wrong
us, shall we not revenge?"

01:23:28.990 --> 01:23:32.540 position:56%
What I want to focus on is
Shakespeare's use of the word wrong.

01:23:32.540 --> 01:23:34.630
What is Shylock speaking about?

01:23:34.630 --> 01:23:39.410
A legal wrong or a moral wrong
or just a semantic wrong?

01:23:39.410 --> 01:23:42.550
If a legal wrong, then we do
not question Shylock's recourse

01:23:42.550 --> 01:23:44.150
to the legal system.

01:23:44.150 --> 01:23:46.840
But if he's speaking about a
moral wrong, and the speech

01:23:46.840 --> 01:23:49.990
as a whole is overwhelmingly
about moral wrong,

01:23:49.990 --> 01:23:51.950
then Shylock's own moral failing is

01:23:51.950 --> 01:23:57.320
that he's using the legal
system to obtain revenge.

01:23:57.320 --> 01:24:00.600
Bassanio in the very next scene
calls attention to the problem

01:24:00.600 --> 01:24:05.820
when he says, quote, "In law,
what plea so tainted and corrupt,

01:24:05.820 --> 01:24:10.860
but being seasoned with a gracious
voice, obscures the show of evil?"

01:24:10.860 --> 01:24:16.270
So, Bassanio knows that law can
dress something up that is corrupt,

01:24:16.270 --> 01:24:19.570
can make it seem to be acceptable.

01:24:19.570 --> 01:24:22.930
Finally, during the
trial scene in Act IV,

01:24:22.930 --> 01:24:27.670 position:56%
Shylock shows his profound blindness
to his own failing when he says,

01:24:27.670 --> 01:24:30.910
"What judgment shall I
dread doing no wrong?"

01:24:30.910 --> 01:24:34.000
He cannot see the wrong that
he does to the legal system

01:24:34.000 --> 01:24:37.890
by making it an accomplice for
revenge notwithstanding his desire

01:24:37.890 --> 01:24:40.620
to make his bond an
instrument of descent.

01:24:40.620 --> 01:24:44.040
So in the process of his trying
to overcome his othering,

01:24:44.040 --> 01:24:50.070
he makes other mistakes,
certainly category mistakes.

01:24:50.070 --> 01:24:53.840
Okay. And then two more points.

01:24:53.840 --> 01:24:56.220
Next, Shylock's conduct
at the trial.

01:24:56.220 --> 01:24:59.560
Fundamentally, even though Shylock
abides by the rules of the court,

01:24:59.560 --> 01:25:03.810
he does not submit himself fully
to the forms of argument expected

01:25:03.810 --> 01:25:06.340
by his adversaries or by the Duke.

01:25:06.340 --> 01:25:11.000 position:56%
So, at least within the construct of
the play as shown by Quentin Skinner

01:25:11.000 --> 01:25:12.840
in his book, <i>Forensic
Shakespeare </i>--

01:25:12.840 --> 01:25:15.800
it's a really wonderful book
about taking apart several

01:25:15.800 --> 01:25:19.080
of Shakespeare's plays and
looking at them from the standpoint

01:25:19.080 --> 01:25:26.260
of rhetoric and forensics that
were available in the Renaissance.

01:25:26.260 --> 01:25:29.790
That the Duke and Portia
expected a very particular form

01:25:29.790 --> 01:25:32.160
of argumentation from Shylock.

01:25:32.160 --> 01:25:33.850
They did not get it.

01:25:33.850 --> 01:25:37.020 position:56%
The expected argument would
attract the rhetorical prescriptions

01:25:37.020 --> 01:25:40.720
of classical authors such
as Cicero and Quintillion.

01:25:40.720 --> 01:25:44.720
Skinner argues that Shylock, by
straying from the prescriptions

01:25:44.720 --> 01:25:47.990
of classical rhetoric,
hurt his own case.

01:25:47.990 --> 01:25:52.030
If Shylock does not adopt the
expected rhetorical strategies,

01:25:52.030 --> 01:25:54.520
is he instead using
argument in ways attended --

01:25:54.520 --> 01:25:58.680
intended to call attention
to his status as other?

01:25:58.680 --> 01:26:02.880
Specifically, how much was
Shylock's rhetoric a product

01:26:02.880 --> 01:26:07.620
of his own Jewish philosophy and
forms of Talmudic argumentation?

01:26:07.620 --> 01:26:10.760
Was the ruling against Shylock
delivered in part out of a failure

01:26:10.760 --> 01:26:14.570
to grasp the difference between
Western forms of argument

01:26:14.570 --> 01:26:17.300
and Jewish forms of argument?

01:26:17.300 --> 01:26:20.460
Without attempting anything more
than suggestion at this point,

01:26:20.460 --> 01:26:22.640
I would direction your
attention to a work

01:26:22.640 --> 01:26:25.900
such David A. Frank's
article, "Arguing With God,

01:26:25.900 --> 01:26:28.970
Talmudic Discourse and
the Jewish Countermodel."

01:26:28.970 --> 01:26:31.600
Frank argues that the Jewish
form of argument is founded

01:26:31.600 --> 01:26:34.550
on freedom rather than necessity.

01:26:34.550 --> 01:26:39.350
He opposes the Jewish act of
argumentation, the classical forms

01:26:39.350 --> 01:26:44.410
of debate, that depend rather on
apodictic reasoning or reasoning

01:26:44.410 --> 01:26:50.550 position:56%
that goes to a clear certainty, a
standard that forecloses discussion.

01:26:50.550 --> 01:26:55.210
Frank quotes two writers
on rhetoric and says,

01:26:55.210 --> 01:26:58.840
"Recourse to argumentation assumes
the establishment of a community

01:26:58.840 --> 01:27:05.170
of minds which, while it lasts,
excludes the use of violence."

01:27:05.170 --> 01:27:07.110
But Shylock is read --

01:27:07.110 --> 01:27:10.210
so my argument reverses
the traditional reading

01:27:10.210 --> 01:27:13.640
of the trial scene where Shylock
is read as advocating violence,

01:27:13.640 --> 01:27:16.470
the penalty, and Portia, mercy.

01:27:16.470 --> 01:27:20.020
However, the violence of the
decision and sentence happen

01:27:20.020 --> 01:27:23.800
because they're moving toward
a conclusion, in Western style,

01:27:23.800 --> 01:27:26.010
that is, inevitably, with closure,

01:27:26.010 --> 01:27:30.390
when Shylock must surrender his
wealth and convert to Christianity.

01:27:30.390 --> 01:27:31.690
No one will ever be able

01:27:31.690 --> 01:27:33.730
to show whether Shylock
would have shown mercy

01:27:33.730 --> 01:27:37.090
to Antonio had he won his case.

01:27:37.090 --> 01:27:38.760
Perhaps the point would
have been made

01:27:38.760 --> 01:27:43.630
and the discussion could
continue with mercy in the offing.

01:27:43.630 --> 01:27:47.150
Ins other words, that Shylock
was arguing from a point

01:27:47.150 --> 01:27:51.600
of open-endedness rather
than closure.

01:27:51.600 --> 01:27:56.920
Okay. I'm going to skip over some
of this, and I just want to get

01:27:56.920 --> 01:28:00.050
to one final thing
which is from Bocaccio.

01:28:00.050 --> 01:28:05.530
So this is an argument
focused on the systemic failure

01:28:05.530 --> 01:28:07.800
of the Venetian state to take

01:28:07.800 --> 01:28:11.790
into account the Jews
and their perspective.

01:28:11.790 --> 01:28:14.240
Shylock and the Jews
had no role in debating

01:28:14.240 --> 01:28:17.250
or adopting the laws
enforced by the court.

01:28:17.250 --> 01:28:21.290
Is it equitable to have those laws
applied cruelly and exactingly

01:28:21.290 --> 01:28:23.660
to those excluded from the polis?

01:28:23.660 --> 01:28:26.010
In the <i>Nicomachean Ethics</i>
Aristotle wrote that

01:28:26.010 --> 01:28:29.240
"what is called judgment in
reference to which we assert

01:28:29.240 --> 01:28:32.250
that people are sympathetic
judges and have judgment,"

01:28:32.250 --> 01:28:35.590
is the correct decision
as to what is equitable.

01:28:35.590 --> 01:28:38.760
Madonna Filippa in
Boccaccio's <i>Decameron </i>,

01:28:38.760 --> 01:28:40.800
written in the 14th century,

01:28:40.800 --> 01:28:44.860
articulated very clearly the
principle that is not equitable

01:28:44.860 --> 01:28:48.990
to hold one group, in her case,
women, accountable to laws

01:28:48.990 --> 01:28:53.040 position:56%
that have been adopted without
their participation or contribution.

01:28:53.040 --> 01:28:56.780
In the case at issue, Madonna
Filippa is accused of adultery,

01:28:56.780 --> 01:29:00.010
but she argues that,
quote, "Every man

01:29:00.010 --> 01:29:04.610 position:56%
and woman should be equal before the
law and laws must have the consent

01:29:04.610 --> 01:29:07.250
of those who are affected by them.

01:29:07.250 --> 01:29:10.000
These conditions are not
fulfilled in the present instant

01:29:10.000 --> 01:29:15.280
because this law only applies to us
poor women who are much better able

01:29:15.280 --> 01:29:18.930
than men to bestow
our favors liberally.

01:29:18.930 --> 01:29:23.760
Moreover, when this law was made,
no woman gave her consent to it,

01:29:23.760 --> 01:29:28.710
nor was any woman ever so much
as -- even to much as consulted.

01:29:28.710 --> 01:29:33.380
It can, therefore, justly be
described as a very bad law."

01:29:33.380 --> 01:29:35.970
So there was a very
strong historical argument

01:29:35.970 --> 01:29:37.310
at hand for Shylock.

01:29:37.310 --> 01:29:40.060
Boccaccio was well
before Shakespeare wrote,

01:29:40.060 --> 01:29:43.760
and Shakespeare knew Boccaccio
-- one -- knew his writing.

01:29:43.760 --> 01:29:48.830
One has only to replace women in
Madonna Filippa's speech with Jews.

01:29:48.830 --> 01:29:51.510
And, by the way, Madonna
Filippa was acquitted

01:29:51.510 --> 01:29:54.280
